abstract: >-
  Code and data backing a behavioral study of within-family, across-tier self-recognition
  in Claude 4.x (Opus, Sonnet, Haiku). Forced-choice experiments with two confound controls,
  framing variation, a forgery paradigm, and a raw-API replication show that tier style is
  externally legible and capability-graded, yet being the author confers no advantage over a
  neutral judge of equal-or-lower compute; attribution runs on stereotype, and
  identity-judgment calibration tracks capability. The authoritative dataset is a verified
  clean-room re-run pooled over two independent passes.
